    62	/specifications/
    63	/provenance/
    64	  NNN-title/
    65	    00-assessment.md
    66	    01-brief-shared.md       (if preserved separately)
    67	    01X-perspective-<role>.md
    68	    01-deliberation.md
    69	    02-decisions.md
    70	    03-close.md
    71	    manifests/
    72	    participants.yaml
    73	    archive/                 (if over-threshold raws were archive-packed per read-contract.md §4)
    74	      <slug>/
    75	        manifest.yaml
    76	        0N-chunk.md
    77	/tools/
    78	/applications/
    79	/records/                      (added v7; structured-source-record substrate per records-contract.md v1)
    80	  sessions/                    (phase-1; per-session records replacing pre-v7 SESSION-LOG.md)
   260	
   261	An optional, mode-dependent top-level directory for operator-mediated engine/methodology feedback flowing from external-problem applications back to the self-development source workspace. Non-engine-definition; not copied when the engine is cloned.
   262	
   263	**In external-problem workspaces**, the directory is an **outbox**: the operator places feedback files here when external-application practice surfaces methodology-level friction (unclear spec, kernel §7 gap, dispatcher ambiguity, MAD v4 awkwardness, reference-validation exercise gap, or equivalent). Feedback files should use the naming convention `EF-<external-session-number>-<short-slug>.md`.
   264	
   265	**In the self-development source workspace**, the directory carries three subdirectories:
   266	
   267	- `inbox/` — operator copies feedback files verbatim from external workspaces here. Preserved byte-identically per read-contract §3 (archive-surface preservation discipline extended to feedback).
   268	- `triage/` — per-feedback triage records written by self-development sessions that triage inbox items. Separate file per feedback record. Triage state does not overwrite intake.
   269	- `INDEX.md` — thin index with one line per feedback record and its current status.
   270	
   271	Feedback file frontmatter schema:
   272	
   273	```yaml
   274	---
   275	feedback_id: EF-NNN-<slug>
   276	source_workspace_id: <workspace id>
   277	source_session: NNN
   278	created_at: <ISO-8601>
   279	reported_by: operator | application-agent
   280	target: engine | methodology | other
   281	target_files: [<paths>]
   282	severity: blocker | friction | observation
   283	status: outbound | inbox | triaged | resolved | rejected
   284	---
   285	```
   286	
   287	Feedback file body sections: `## Observation` (what happened in the external application), `## Why It Matters` (what engine/methodology behaviour was implicated), `## Suggested Change` (optional), `## Evidence` (links or copied snippets), `## Application-Scope Disposition` (why the external application did or did not resolve locally).
   288	
   289	Triage file frontmatter schema:
   290	
   291	```yaml
   292	---
   293	feedback_ref: engine-feedback/inbox/EF-<id>.md
   294	triage_session: NNN
   295	status: accepted | deferred | rejected
   296	classification: substantive | minor | non-applicable
   297	opened_issue: open-issues/OI-NNN.md  # optional; present when triage lifts feedback to OI
   298	resolved_by: provenance/NNN-title/  # optional; present when resolution is complete
   299	---
   300	```
   301	
   302	**Read-contract integration**: `engine-feedback/INDEX.md` is default-read in self-development mode when present (per `read-contract.md` v4 §1 item 9). Individual feedback files in `inbox/` and `triage/` are activation-read by reference when `INDEX.md` shows `status: new` or when an OI cross-references them.
   303	
   304	**OI integration**: substantive feedback that warrants OI opening produces a new OI in `open-issues/` following existing conventions; the triage file's `opened_issue:` pointer cross-references the OI. Minor feedback can remain in triage-only.
   305	
   306	**Retention**: feedback intake files preserved verbatim. Neither intake nor triage overwrite each other.
   307	
   308	**Return semantics**: return of feedback from external workspace to self-development is **operator-mediated** — the operator carries the file by copy-paste or equivalent. The engine does not specify automated cross-workspace transport. External application workspaces are independent of each other and of the self-development workspace at the filesystem level; the operator is the transport.
   309	
